# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lattice-cryptography
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] The system is based on the module learning with errors (M-LWE) problem, in conjunction with cyclotomic rings.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] Recently, there has also been a tight formal mathematical security reduction of the ring-LWE problem to MLWE.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] Compared to competing PQ methods, it has typical advantages of lattice-based methods, e.g. in regard to runtime as well as the size of the ciphertexts and the key material.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] Variants with different security levels have been defined: ML-KEM-512 (NIST security level 1), ML-KEM-768 (NIST security level 3), and ML-KEM-1024 (NIST security level 5).
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] At the ML-KEM-768 level, the secret keys are 2400 bytes in size, the public keys 1184, and the ciphertexts 1088.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] With an accordingly optimized implementation, 4 kilobytes of memory can be sufficient for the cryptographic operations.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] Internal hashing operations account for the majority of the runtime, which would thus potentially benefit greatly from corresponding hardware acceleration.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] Prior to standardization, ML-KEM was known under the name Kyber.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] They also developed the related and complementary signature scheme *Dilithium* (later standardized as ML-DSA), as another component of their "Cryptographic Suite for Algebraic Lattices" (CRYSTALS).
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] Like other PQC-KEM methods, Kyber makes extensive use of hashing internally.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] In Kyber's case, variants of Keccak (SHA-3/SHAKE) are used here, to generate pseudorandom numbers, among other things.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] In 2017, the method was submitted to the US National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) for its public selection process for a first standard for quantum-safe cryptographic primitives (NISTPQC).
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] It was the first key encapsulation mechanism that has been selected for standardization (and the only one at the end of the third round of the NIST standardization process).
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] According to a footnote the report announcing the decision, it is conditional on the execution of various patent-related agreements, with NTRU being a fallback option.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] In 2025, within a fourth round of the standardization process, the HQC scheme has been selected for standardization as a fallback.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] In the second phase of the selection process, several parameters of the algorithm were adjusted and the compression of the public keys was dropped.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] Most recently, NIST paid particular attention to costs in terms of runtime and complexity for implementations that mask runtimes in order to prevent corresponding side-channel attacks (SCA).
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] Kyber underwent changes during the NIST standardization process.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] The developers have released a reference implementation into the public domain (or under CC0), which is written in C.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] The program library *liboqs* of the Open Quantum Safe (OQS) project contains an implementation based on that.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] OQS also maintains a quantum-safe Provider module for OpenSSL 3.x, and has integrated its code into BoringSSL.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] The wolfSSL library additionally maintains its own implementation of ML-KEM.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] There are a handful of implementations using various other programming languages from third-party developers, including JavaScript and Java.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] Various (free) optimized hardware implementations exist, including one that is resistant to side-channel attacks.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] The German Federal Office for Information Security is aiming for implementation in Thunderbird, and in this context also an implementation in the Botan program library and corresponding adjustments to the OpenPGP standard.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] Amazon Web Services (AWS) integrated Kyber into their Key Management Service (KMS) in 2020 as a hybrid post-quantum key exchange option for TLS connections.
[src:lattice-cryptography/kyber] In 2023, the encrypted messaging service Signal implemented PQXDH, a Kyber-based post-quantum encryption algorithm, to their Signal Protocol.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] In 2024 NIST announced the Module-Lattice-Based Digital Signature Standard for post-quantum cryptography.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] She then showed a cryptographic hash function whose security is equivalent to the computational hardness of SIS.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] In 1998, Jeffrey Hoffstein, Jill Pipher, and Joseph H.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Silverman introduced a lattice-based public-key encryption scheme, known as NTRU.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] However, their scheme is not known to be at least as hard as solving a worst-case lattice problem.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] The first lattice-based public-key encryption scheme whose security was proven under worst-case hardness assumptions was introduced by Oded Regev in 2005, together with the learning with errors problem (LWE).
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Since then, much follow-up work has focused on improving Regev's security proof and improving the efficiency of the original scheme.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Much more work has been devoted to constructing additional cryptographic primitives based on LWE and related problems.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] For example, in 2009, Craig Gentry introduced the first fully homomorphic encryption scheme, which was based on a lattice problem.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] In linear algebra, a lattice $L\subset \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is the set of all integer linear combinations of vectors from a basis $\{\mathbf {b} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {b} _{n}\}$ of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] In other words, $L={\Big \{}\sum a_{i}\mathbf {b} _{i}:a_{i}\in \mathbb {Z} {\Big \}}.$ For example, $\mathbb {Z} ^{n}$ is a lattice, generated by the standard basis for $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Crucially, the basis for a lattice is not unique.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] The most important lattice-based computational problem is the shortest vector problem (SVP or sometimes GapSVP), which asks for an approximate minimal Euclidean length of a non-zero lattice vector.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] This problem is thought to be hard to solve efficiently, even with approximation factors that are polynomial in n , and even with a quantum computer.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Many (though not all) lattice-based cryptographic constructions are known to be secure if SVP is in fact hard in this regime.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] This section presents selected lattice-based schemes, grouped by primitive.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] This section lists a selection of lattice-based schemes for the purpose of digital signatures.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] CRYSTALS-Dilithium or simply Dilithium is built upon module-LWE and module-SIS.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Dilithium was selected by the NIST as the basis for a digital signature standard.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] According to a message from Ray Perlner, writing on behalf of the NIST PQC team, the NIST module-LWE signing standard is to be based on version 3.1 of the Dilithium specification.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] NIST's changes on Dilithium 3.1 intend to support additional randomness in signing (hedged signing) and other improvements.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Dilithium was one of the two digital signature schemes initially chosen by the NIST in their post-quantum cryptography process, the other one being SPHINCS+, which is not based on lattices but on hashes.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] In August 2023, NIST published FIPS 204 (Initial Public Draft), and started calling Dilithium "Module-Lattice-Based Digital Signature Algorithm" (ML-DSA).
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] As of October 2023, ML-DSA was being implemented as a part of Libgcrypt, according to Falko Strenzke.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] In August 2024, NIST officially standardized CRYSTALS-Dilithium under the name ML-DSA, establishing it as the primary standard (FIPS 204) for quantum-resistant digital signatures.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Lattice-based cryptographic constructions hold a great promise for public-key post-quantum cryptography.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Indeed, the main alternative forms of public-key cryptography are schemes based on the hardness of factoring and related problems and schemes based on the hardness of the discrete logarithm and related problems.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] However, both factoring and the discrete logarithm problem are known to be solvable in polynomial time on a quantum computer.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Furthermore, algorithms for factorization tend to yield algorithms for discrete logarithm, and conversely.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] This further motivates the study of constructions based on alternative assumptions, such as the hardness of lattice problems.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Many lattice-based cryptographic schemes are known to be secure assuming the *worst-case* hardness of certain lattice problems.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] I.e., if there exists an algorithm that can efficiently break the cryptographic scheme with non-negligible probability, then there exists an efficient algorithm that solves a certain lattice problem on any input.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] However, for the practical lattice-based constructions (such as schemes based on NTRU and even schemes based on LWE with efficient parameters), meaningful reduction-based guarantees of security are not known.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Some authors who have investigated concrete security for lattice-based cryptosystems have found that the provable security results for such systems do not provide any meaningful concrete security for practical values of the parameters.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] For many cryptographic primitives, the only known constructions are based on lattices or closely related objects.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] These primitives include fully homomorphic encryption, indistinguishability obfuscation, cryptographic multilinear maps, and functional encryption.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] In computer science, **lattice problems** are a class of optimization problems related to mathematical objects called *lattices*.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] The conjectured intractability of such problems is central to the construction of secure lattice-based cryptosystems: lattice problems are an example of NP-hard problems which have been shown to be average-case hard, providing a test case for the security of cryptographic algorithms.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] In addition, some lattice problems which are worst-case hard can be used as a basis for extremely secure cryptographic schemes.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] The use of worst-case hardness in such schemes makes them among the very few schemes that are very likely secure even against quantum computers.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] For applications in such cryptosystems, lattices over vector spaces (often $\mathbb {Q} ^{n}$ ) or free modules (often $\mathbb {Z} ^{n}$ ) are generally considered.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] For all the problems below, assume that we are given (in addition to other more specific inputs) a basis for the vector space *V* and a norm *N*.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] The norm usually considered is the Euclidean norm *L*2.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] However, other norms (such as *L**p*) are also considered and show up in a variety of results.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] In the SVP, a basis of a vector space *V* and a norm *N* (often *L*2) are given for a lattice *L* and one must find the shortest non-zero vector in *V*, as measured by *N*, in *L*.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] In other words, the algorithm should output a non-zero vector *v* such that ⁠ $\|v\|_{N}=\lambda (L)$ ⁠.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] In the following, the size of the problem is specified by *n*, the dimension of the vector space *V*.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] In the γ-approximation version SVPγ, one must find a non-zero lattice vector of length at most $\gamma \cdot \lambda (L)$ for given ⁠ $\gamma \geq 1$ ⁠.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] The exact version of the problem is only known to be NP-hard for randomized reductions.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] By contrast, the corresponding problem with respect to the uniform norm is known to be NP-hard.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] The former class of algorithms most notably includes lattice enumeration and random sampling reduction, while the latter includes lattice sieving, computing the Voronoi cell of the lattice, and discrete Gaussian sampling.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] An open problem is whether algorithms for solving exact SVP exist running in single exponential time ( $2^{O(n)}$ ) and requiring memory scaling polynomially in the lattice dimension.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] To solve the γ-approximation version SVPγ for $\gamma >1$ for the Euclidean norm, the best known approaches are based on using lattice basis reduction.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] For large ⁠ $\gamma =2^{\Omega (n)}$ ⁠, the Lenstra–Lenstra–Lovász (LLL) algorithm can find a solution in time polynomial in the lattice dimension.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] For small $\gamma$ , larger $\beta$ are needed to find sufficiently short lattice vectors, and the algorithm takes longer to find a solution.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] The BKZ algorithm internally uses an exact SVP algorithm as a subroutine (running in lattices of dimension at most $\beta$ ), and its overall complexity is closely related to the costs of these SVP calls in dimension ⁠ $\beta$ ⁠.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] The problem GapSVPβ consists of distinguishing between the instances of SVP in which the length of the shortest vector is at most 1 or larger than ⁠ $\beta$ ⁠, where $\beta$ can be a fixed function of the dimension of the lattice ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] Given a basis for the lattice, the algorithm must decide whether $\lambda (L)\leq 1$ or ⁠ $\lambda (L)>\beta$ ⁠.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] Like other promise problems, the algorithm is allowed to err on all other cases.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] Yet another version of the problem is GapSVPζ,γ for some functions ζ and γ.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] The input to the algorithm is a basis B and a number d .
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] It is assured that all the vectors in the Gram–Schmidt orthogonalization are of length at least 1, and that $\lambda (L(B))\leq \zeta (n)$ and that ⁠ $1\leq d\leq \zeta (n)/\gamma (n)$ ⁠, where n is the dimension.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] The algorithm must accept if ⁠ $\lambda (L(B))\leq d$ ⁠, and reject if ⁠ $\lambda (L(B))\geq \gamma (n)\cdot d$ ⁠.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] For large $\zeta$ (i.e. ⁠ $\zeta (n)>2^{n/2}$ ⁠), the problem is equivalent to GapSVPγ because a preprocessing done using the LLL algorithm makes the second condition (and hence, ⁠ $\zeta$ ⁠) redundant.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] In CVP, a basis of a vector space *V* and a metric *M* (often *L*2) are given for a lattice *L*, as well as a vector *v* in *V* but not necessarily in *L*.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] It is desired to find the vector in *L* closest to *v* (as measured by *M*).
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] In the $\gamma$ -approximation version CVPγ, one must find a lattice vector at distance at most $\gamma$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] The closest vector problem is a generalization of the shortest vector problem.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] It is easy to show that given an oracle for CVPγ (defined below), one can solve SVPγ by making some queries to the oracle.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] The naive method to find the shortest vector by calling the CVPγ oracle to find the closest vector to 0 does not work because 0 is itself a lattice vector and the algorithm could potentially output 0.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] The reduction from SVPγ to CVPγ is as follows: Suppose that the input to the SVPγ is the basis for lattice $B=[b_{1},b_{2},\ldots ,b_{n}]$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] The claim is that the shortest vector in the set $\{x_{i}-b_{i}\}$ is the shortest vector in the given lattice.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] Goldreich et al. showed that any hardness of SVP implies the same hardness for CVP.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] Using PCP tools, Arora et al. showed that CVP is hard to approximate within factor $2^{\log ^{1-\epsilon }(n)}$ unless $\operatorname {NP} \subseteq \operatorname {DTIME} (2^{\operatorname {poly} (\log n)})$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] Dinur et al. strengthened this by giving a NP-hardness result with $\epsilon =(\log \log n)^{c}$ for $c<1/2$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] Algorithms for CVP, especially the Fincke and Pohst variant, have been used for data detection in multiple-input multiple-output (MIMO) wireless communication systems (for coded and uncoded signals).
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] In this context it is called *sphere decoding* due to the radius used internal to many CVP solutions.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] It has been applied in the field of the integer ambiguity resolution of carrier-phase GNSS (GPS).
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] It is called the *LAMBDA method* in that field.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] In the same field, the general CVP problem is referred to as *Integer Least Squares*.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] This problem is similar to the GapSVP problem.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] The opposite condition is that the closest lattice vector is at a distance $1<\lambda (L)\leq \beta$ , hence the name *Gap*CVP.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] The problem is trivially contained in NP for any approximation factor.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] Schnorr, in 1987, showed that deterministic polynomial time algorithms can solve the problem for $\beta =2^{O(n(\log \log n)^{2}/\log n)}$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] Ajtai et al. showed that probabilistic algorithms can achieve a slightly better approximation factor of $\beta =2^{O(n\log \log n/\log n)}$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] In 1993, Banaszczyk showed that GapCVPn is in ${\mathsf {NP\cap coNP}}$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] In 2000, Goldreich and Goldwasser showed that $\beta ={\sqrt {n/\log n}}$ puts the problem in both NP and coAM.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] In 2005, Aharonov and Regev showed that for some constant c , the problem with $\beta =c{\sqrt {n}}$ is in ${\mathsf {NP\cap coNP}}$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] For lower bounds, Dinur et al. showed in 1998 that the problem is NP-hard for $\beta =n^{o(1/\log {\log {n}})}$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] Given a lattice L of dimension *n*, the algorithm must output *n* linearly independent $v_{1},v_{2},\ldots ,v_{n}$ so that $\max \|v_{i}\|\leq \max _{B}\|b_{i}\|$ , where the right-hand side considers all bases $B=\{b_{1},\ldots ,b_{n}\}$ of the lattice.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] In the $\gamma$ -approximate version, given a lattice L with dimension *n*, one must find *n* linearly independent vectors $v_{1},v_{2},\ldots ,v_{n}$ of length ⁠ $\max \|v_{i}\|\leq \gamma \lambda _{n}(L)$ ⁠, where $\lambda _{n}(L)$ is the ⁠ n ⁠th successive minimum of ⁠ L ⁠.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] Given a vector such that its distance from the lattice is at most $\lambda (L)/2$ , the algorithm must output the closest lattice vector to it.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] Given a basis for the lattice, the algorithm must find the largest distance (or in some versions, its approximation) from any vector to the lattice.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] Many problems become easier if the input basis consists of short vectors.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] An algorithm that solves the Shortest Basis Problem (SBP) must, given a lattice basis ⁠ B ⁠, output an equivalent basis $B'$ such that the length of the longest vector in $B'$ is as short as possible.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] The approximation version SBPγ problem consist of finding a basis whose longest vector is at most $\gamma$ times longer than the longest vector in the shortest basis.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] Average-case hardness of problems forms a basis for proofs-of-security for most cryptographic schemes.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] However, experimental evidence suggests that most NP-hard problems lack this property: they are probably only worst case hard.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] Many lattice problems have been conjectured or proven to be average-case hard, making them an attractive class of problems to base cryptographic schemes on.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] Moreover, worst-case hardness of some lattice problems have been used to create secure cryptographic schemes.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] The above lattice problems are easy to solve if the algorithm is provided with a "good" basis.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] Lattice reduction algorithms aim, given a basis for a lattice, to output a new basis consisting of relatively short, nearly orthogonal vectors.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] The Lenstra–Lenstra–Lovász lattice basis reduction algorithm (LLL) was an early efficient algorithm for this problem which could output an almost reduced lattice basis in polynomial time.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] This algorithm and its further refinements were used to break several cryptographic schemes, establishing its status as a very important tool in cryptanalysis.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] The success of LLL on experimental data led to a belief that lattice reduction might be an easy problem in practice; however, this belief was challenged in the late 1990s, when several new results on the hardness of lattice problems were obtained, starting with the result of Ajtai.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] In his seminal papers, Ajtai showed that the SVP problem was NP-hard and discovered some connections between the worst-case complexity and average-case complexity of some lattice problems.
[src:lattice-cryptography/lattice-problem] Building on these results, Ajtai and Dwork created a public-key cryptosystem whose security could be proven using only the worst case hardness of a certain version of SVP, thus making it the first result to have used worst-case hardness to create secure systems.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] In cryptography, **learning with errors** (**LWE**) is a mathematical problem that is widely used to create secure encryption algorithms.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] It is based on the idea of representing secret information as a set of equations with errors.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] In other words, LWE is a way to hide the value of a secret by introducing noise to it.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] In more technical terms, it refers to the computational problem of inferring a linear n -ary function f over a finite ring from given samples $y_{i}=f(\mathbf {x} _{i})$ some of which may be erroneous.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] The LWE problem is conjectured to be hard to solve, and thus to be useful in cryptography.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] More precisely, the LWE problem is defined as follows.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Let $\mathbb {Z} _{q}$ denote the ring of integers modulo q and let $\mathbb {Z} _{q}^{n}$ denote the set of n -vectors over $\mathbb {Z} _{q}$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Furthermore, the deviation from the equality is according to some known noise model.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] The problem calls for finding the function f , or some close approximation thereof, with high probability.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] The LWE problem was introduced by Oded Regev in 2005 (who won the 2018 Gödel Prize for this work); it is a generalization of the parity learning problem.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Regev showed that the LWE problem is as hard to solve as several worst-case lattice problems.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Subsequently, the LWE problem has been used as a hardness assumption to create public-key cryptosystems, such as the ring learning with errors key exchange by Peikert.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Denote by $\mathbb {T} =\mathbb {R} /\mathbb {Z}$ the additive group on reals modulo one.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Let $\mathbf {s} \in \mathbb {Z} _{q}^{n}$ be a fixed vector.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Let $\phi$ be a fixed probability distribution over $\mathbb {T}$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Denote by $A_{\mathbf {s} ,\phi }$ the distribution on $\mathbb {Z} _{q}^{n}\times \mathbb {T}$ obtained as follows.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] The **learning with errors problem** $\mathrm {LWE} _{q,\phi }$ is to find $\mathbf {s} \in \mathbb {Z} _{q}^{n}$ , given access to polynomially many samples of choice from $A_{\mathbf {s} ,\phi }$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] The **LWE** problem described above is the *search* version of the problem.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] In the *decision* version (**DLWE**), the goal is to distinguish between noisy inner products and uniformly random samples from $\mathbb {Z} _{q}^{n}\times \mathbb {T}$ (practically, some discretized version of it).
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Regev showed that the *decision* and *search* versions are equivalent when q is a prime bounded by some polynomial in n .
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Intuitively, if we have a procedure for the search problem, the decision version can be solved easily: just feed the input samples for the decision problem to the solver for the search problem.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] If the solver returns a candidate $\mathbf {s}$ , for all i , calculate $\{\langle \mathbf {a} _{i},\mathbf {s} \rangle -\mathbf {b} _{i}\}$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] If the samples are from an LWE distribution, then the results of this calculation will be distributed according $\chi$ , but if the samples are uniformly random, these quantities will be distributed uniformly as well.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] For the other direction, given a solver for the decision problem, the search version can be solved as follows: Recover $\mathbf {s}$ one coordinate at a time.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] To obtain the first coordinate, $\mathbf {s} _{1}$ , make a guess $k\in \mathbb {Z} _{q}$ , and do the following.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Choose a number $r\in \mathbb {Z} _{q}$ uniformly at random.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Send the transformed samples to the decision solver.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] If the guess k was correct, the transformation takes the distribution $A_{\mathbf {s} ,\chi }$ to itself, and otherwise, since q is prime, it takes it to the uniform distribution.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] So, given a polynomial-time solver for the decision problem that errs with very small probability, since q is bounded by some polynomial in n , it only takes polynomial time to guess every possible value for k and use the solver to see which one is correct.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] After obtaining $\mathbf {s} _{1}$ , we follow an analogous procedure for each other coordinate $\mathbf {s} _{j}$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Namely, we transform our $\mathbf {b} _{i}$ samples the same way, and transform our $\mathbf {a} _{i}$ samples by calculating $\mathbf {a} _{i}+(0,\ldots ,r,\ldots ,0)$ , where the r is in the $j^{\text{th}}$ coordinate.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Peikert showed that this reduction, with a small modification, works for any q that is a product of distinct, small (polynomial in n ) primes.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] The main idea is if $q=q_{1}q_{2}\cdots q_{t}$ , for each $q_{\ell }$ , guess and check to see if $\mathbf {s} _{j}$ is congruent to $0\mod q_{\ell }$ , and then use the Chinese remainder theorem to recover $\mathbf {s} _{j}$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Regev showed the random self-reducibility of the **LWE** and **DLWE** problems for arbitrary q and $\chi$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Then there would be some distinguisher ${\mathcal {A}}$ , who, given samples $\{(\mathbf {a} _{i},\mathbf {b} _{i})\}$ , could tell whether they were uniformly random or from $A_{\mathbf {s} ',\chi }$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Thus, no such ${\mathcal {S}}$ can exist, meaning **LWE** and **DLWE** are (up to a polynomial factor) as hard in the average case as they are in the worst case.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Let $D_{L,r}$ denote the discrete Gaussian distribution on L of width r for a lattice L and real $r>0$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] The probability of each $x\in L$ is proportional to $\rho _{r}(x)$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] The *discrete Gaussian sampling problem* (DGS) is defined as follows: An instance of $DGS_{\phi }$ is given by an n -dimensional lattice L and a number $r\geq \phi (L)$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] The goal is to output a sample from $D_{L,r}$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Regev shows that there is a reduction from $\operatorname {GapSVP} _{100{\sqrt {n}}\gamma (n)}$ to $DGS_{{\sqrt {n}}\gamma (n)/\lambda (L^{*})}$ for any function $\gamma (n)\geq 1$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Regev then shows that there exists an efficient quantum algorithm for $DGS_{{\sqrt {2n}}\eta _{\varepsilon }(L)/\alpha }$ given access to an oracle for $\mathrm {LWE} _{q,\Psi _{\alpha }}$ for integer q and $\alpha \in (0,1)$ such that $\alpha q>2{\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Although the proof of this assertion works for any q , for creating a cryptosystem, the modulus q has to be polynomial in n .
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] The **LWE** problem serves as a versatile problem used in construction of several cryptosystems.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] In 2005, Regev showed that the decision version of LWE is hard assuming quantum hardness of the lattice problems $\mathrm {GapSVP} _{\gamma }$ (for $\gamma$ as above) and $\mathrm {SIVP} _{t}$ with $t=O(n/\alpha )$ ).
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] In 2009, Peikert proved a similar result assuming only the classical hardness of the related problem $\mathrm {GapSVP} _{\zeta ,\gamma }$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] The disadvantage of Peikert's result is that it bases itself on a non-standard version of an easier (when compared to SIVP) problem GapSVP.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Regev proposed a public-key cryptosystem based on the hardness of the **LWE** problem.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] The cryptosystem as well as the proof of security and correctness are completely classical.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] The system is characterized by $m,q$ and a probability distribution $\chi$ on $\mathbb {T}$ .
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] The proof of correctness follows from choice of parameters and some probability analysis.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] Peikert proposed a system that is secure even against any chosen-ciphertext attack.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] The idea of using LWE and Ring LWE for key exchange was proposed and filed at the University of Cincinnati in 2011 by Jintai Ding.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] The idea comes from the associativity of matrix multiplications, and the errors are used to provide the security.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] The paper appeared in 2012 after a provisional patent application was filed in 2012.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] The security of the protocol is proven based on the hardness of solving the LWE problem.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] In 2014, Peikert presented a key-transport scheme following the same basic idea of Ding's, where the new idea of sending an additional 1-bit signal for rounding in Ding's construction is also used.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] The "new hope" implementation selected for Google's post-quantum experiment, uses Peikert's scheme with variation in the error distribution.
[src:lattice-cryptography/learning-with-errors] A RLWE version of the classic Feige–Fiat–Shamir Identification protocol was created and converted to a digital signature in 2011 by Lyubashevsky.
[src:lattice-cryptography/ntru] The first version of the system, which was called NTRU, was developed in 1996 by mathematicians Jeffrey Hoffstein, Jill Pipher, and Joseph H.
[src:lattice-cryptography/ntru] That same year, the developers of NTRU joined with Daniel Lieman and founded the company NTRU Cryptosystems, Inc., and were given a patent on the cryptosystem.
[src:lattice-cryptography/ntru] The name "NTRU", chosen for the company and soon applied to the system as well, was originally derived from the pun *Number Theorists 'R' Us* or, alternatively, stood for *Number Theory Research Unit*.
[src:lattice-cryptography/ntru] In 2009, the company was acquired by Security Innovation, a software security corporation.
[src:lattice-cryptography/ntru] In 2013, Damien Stehle and Ron Steinfeld created a provably secure version of NTRU, which is being studied by a post-quantum crypto group chartered by the European Commission.
[src:lattice-cryptography/ntru] In May 2016, Daniel Bernstein, Chitchanok Chuengsatiansup, Tanja Lange and Christine van Vredendaal released NTRU Prime, which adds defenses against a potential attack on NTRU by eliminating algebraic structure they considered worrisome.
[src:lattice-cryptography/ntru] However, after more than 20 years of scrutiny, no concrete approach to attack the original NTRU by exploiting its algebraic structure has been found so far.
[src:lattice-cryptography/ntru] NTRU became a finalist in the third round of NIST's Post-Quantum Cryptography Standardization project, whereas NTRU Prime became an alternate candidate.
[src:lattice-cryptography/ntru] At equivalent cryptographic strength, NTRU performs costly private-key operations much faster than RSA does.
[src:lattice-cryptography/ntru] The time of performing an RSA private operation increases as the cube of the key size, whereas that of an NTRU operation increases quadratically.
[src:lattice-cryptography/ntru] In 2010, the Department of Electrical Engineering, University of Leuven, noted that "[using] a modern GTX280 GPU, a throughput of up to 200000 encryptions per second can be reached at a security level of 256 bits.
[src:lattice-cryptography/ntru] Unlike RSA and elliptic-curve cryptography, NTRU is not known to be vulnerable to attacks from quantum computers.
[src:lattice-cryptography/ntru] The European Union's PQCRYPTO project (Horizon 2020 ICT-645622) is evaluating the provably secure Stehle–Steinfeld version of NTRU (not original NTRU algorithm itself) as a potential European standard.
[src:lattice-cryptography/ntru] However the Stehle–Steinfeld version of NTRU is "significantly less efficient than the original scheme".
[src:lattice-cryptography/ntru] Originally, NTRU was only available as a proprietary, for-pay library, and open-source authors were threatened with legal action.
[src:lattice-cryptography/ntru] It was not until 2011 that the first open-source implementation appeared, and in 2013, Security Innovation exempted open-source projects from having to get a patent license and released an NTRU reference implementation under the GPL v2.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Mosca's theorem provides the risk analysis framework that helps organizations identify how quickly they need to start migrating.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Their work has gained attention from academics and industry through the PQCrypto conference series hosted since 2006, several workshops on Quantum Safe Cryptography hosted by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI), and the Institute for Quantum Computing.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The rumoured existence of widespread harvest now, decrypt later programs has also been seen as a motivation for the early introduction of post-quantum algorithms, as data recorded now may still remain sensitive many years into the future.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In contrast to the threat quantum computing poses to current public-key algorithms, most current symmetric cryptographic algorithms and hash functions are considered to be relatively secure against attacks by quantum computers.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] While the quantum Grover's algorithm does speed up attacks against symmetric ciphers, doubling the key size can effectively counteract these attacks.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Thus post-quantum symmetric cryptography does not need to differ significantly from current symmetric cryptography.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) released final versions of its first three Post-Quantum Cryptography Standards.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The transition from classical public-key cryptography to post-quantum cryptography (PQC) is considered a long-term, multi-phase process due to the widespread deployment of cryptographic infrastructure across digital systems.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Migration planning is influenced by factors such as data longevity requirements, regulatory guidance, interoperability constraints, and the operational complexity of replacing embedded cryptographic components.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] One commonly cited risk model is Mosca’s theorem, which estimates the urgency of migration by comparing three time horizons: the time required to transition systems (X), the time during which data must remain secure (Y), and the estimated arrival of cryptographically relevant quantum computers (Z).
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] If X + Y > Z, migration is considered urgent.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] A major concern motivating early transition is the “harvest now, decrypt later” threat model, in which encrypted data is intercepted and stored with the intention of decrypting it once large-scale quantum computers become available.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Migration strategies frequently emphasize crypto-agility, the capability of systems to rapidly replace cryptographic primitives without major architectural changes.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Hybrid cryptographic deployments where classical and post-quantum algorithms are used simultaneously have been tested in protocols such as Transport Layer Security (TLS) to reduce transitional risk.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In 2024, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) finalized its first post-quantum cryptography standards, including module-lattice-based key encapsulation and digital signature schemes, providing a foundation for structured migration in governmental and commercial systems.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] International organizations and national cybersecurity agencies have published coordinated roadmaps outlining phased adoption timelines, risk assessments, and procurement guidelines to facilitate a systematic transition.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Because the transition to post-quantum cryptography is expected to take many years, organizations increasingly monitor advances in quantum computing to assess whether migration timelines remain appropriate.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Rather than relying on a single measurement, researchers and cybersecurity agencies evaluate multiple technical indicators that together provide a more meaningful assessment of progress toward cryptographically relevant quantum computers (CRQCs).
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Physical qubit counts alone are generally considered an incomplete measure of cryptographic capability because large numbers of noisy physical qubits may not be able to perform the long, fault-tolerant computations required for practical cryptanalysis.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Consequently, greater emphasis is often placed on advances in logical qubits, quantum error correction, gate fidelity, circuit depth, and the successful implementation of quantum algorithms such as Shor's algorithm on increasingly complex problems.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Together, these technical and institutional indicators help governments, industry, and researchers evaluate the pace of quantum computing development and adjust long-term migration strategies as new evidence becomes available.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Digital infrastructures require robust cybersecurity.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Cryptographic systems are vital to protect the confidentiality and authenticity of data.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Quantum computing will be a threat to many of the classical cryptographic algorithms, which are used to achieve these protection goals but are only secure against classical computers.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Data that is currently not quantum-safe, whether it is stored or transmitted, and that must remain confidential for a long time, may be compromised in the future by quantum computers (“harvest now, decrypt later” attacks).
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In addition, authenticity will also be jeopardised by quantum computers.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The threat that quantum computing poses to cybersecurity can be countered by a timely, comprehensive and coordinated transition to post-quantum cryptography (PQC).
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This approach includes cryptographic systems such as learning with errors, ring learning with errors (ring-LWE), the ring learning with errors key exchange and the ring learning with errors signature, the older NTRU or GGH encryption schemes, and the newer NTRU signature and BLISS signatures.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Some of these schemes like NTRU encryption have been studied for many years without anyone finding a feasible attack.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Others like the ring-LWE algorithms have proofs that their security reduces to a worst-case problem.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The Post-Quantum Cryptography Study Group sponsored by the European Commission suggested that the Stehle–Steinfeld variant of NTRU be studied for standardization rather than the NTRU algorithm.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Studies have indicated that NTRU may have more secure properties than other lattice based algorithms.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Two lattice-based algorithms, ML-KEM (commonly known as Kyber) and ML-DSA (commonly known as Dilithium) were among the first post-quantum algorithms standardised by NIST.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This includes cryptographic systems such as the Unbalanced Oil and Vinegar signature scheme which is based on the difficulty of solving systems of multivariate equations.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Various attempts to build secure multivariate equation encryption schemes have been broken, notably the Rainbow signature.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This includes cryptographic systems such as Lamport signatures, the Merkle signature scheme, the XMSS, the SPHINCS, the WOTS and the SPHINCS+ schemes.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Hash based digital signatures were invented in the late 1970s by Ralph Merkle and have been studied ever since as an interesting alternative to number-theoretic digital signatures like RSA and DSA.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Their primary drawback is that for any hash-based public key, there is a limit on the number of signatures that can be signed using the corresponding set of private keys.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This fact reduced interest in these signatures until interest was revived due to the desire for cryptography that was resistant to attack by quantum computers.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] There appear to be no patents on the Merkle signature scheme and there exist many non-patented hash functions that could be used with these schemes.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The stateful hash-based signature scheme XMSS developed by a team of researchers under the direction of Johannes Buchmann is described in RFC 8391.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Note that all the above schemes are one-time or bounded-time signatures.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Moni Naor and Moti Yung invented UOWHF hashing in 1989 and designed a signature based on hashing (the Naor-Yung scheme) which can be unlimited-time in use (the first such signature that does not require trapdoor properties).
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This includes cryptographic systems which rely on error-correcting codes, such as the McEliece and Niederreiter encryption algorithms and the related Courtois, Finiasz and Sendrier Signature scheme.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The original McEliece signature using random Goppa codes has withstood scrutiny for over 40 years.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] However, many variants of the McEliece scheme, which seek to introduce more structure into the code used in order to reduce the size of the keys, have been shown to be insecure.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The Post-Quantum Cryptography Study Group sponsored by the European Commission has recommended the McEliece public key encryption system as a candidate for long term protection against attacks by quantum computers.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In 2025, NIST announced plans to standardize the code-based HQC encryption algorithm.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] These cryptographic systems rely on the properties of isogeny graphs of elliptic curves (and higher-dimensional abelian varieties) over finite fields, in particular supersingular isogeny graphs, to create cryptographic systems.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Another widely noticed construction, *SIDH/SIKE*, was spectacularly broken in 2022.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The attack is however specific to the SIDH/SIKE family of schemes and does not generalize to other isogeny-based constructions.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Using sufficiently large key sizes, the symmetric key cryptographic systems like AES and SNOW 3G are already resistant to attack by a quantum computer.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Further, key management systems and protocols that use symmetric key cryptography instead of public key cryptography, like Kerberos and the 3GPP Mobile Network Authentication Structure, are also inherently secure against attack by a quantum computer.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Given its widespread deployment in the world, some researchers recommend expanded use of Kerberos-like symmetric key management as an efficient way to get post-quantum cryptography today.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In cryptography research, it is desirable to prove the equivalence of a cryptographic algorithm and a known hard mathematical problem.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] These proofs are often called "security reductions", and are used to demonstrate the difficulty of cracking the encryption algorithm.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In other words, the security of a given cryptographic algorithm is reduced to the security of a known hard problem.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Researchers are actively looking for security reductions in the prospects for post-quantum cryptography.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In some versions of Ring-LWE there is a security reduction to the shortest-vector problem (SVP) in a lattice as a lower bound on the security.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Specific ring-LWE systems that have provable security reductions include a variant of Lyubashevsky's ring-LWE signatures defined in a paper by Güneysu, Lyubashevsky, and Pöppelmann.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The GLYPH signature scheme is a variant of the Güneysu, Lyubashevsky, and Pöppelmann (GLP) signature which takes into account research results that have come after the publication of the GLP signature in 2012.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Another Ring-LWE signature is Ring-TESLA.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] There also exists a "derandomized variant" of LWE, called Learning with Rounding (LWR), which yields "improved speedup (by eliminating sampling small errors from a Gaussian-like distribution with deterministic errors) and bandwidth".
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] While LWE uses the addition of a small error to conceal the lower bits, LWR uses rounding for the same purpose.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The security of the NTRU encryption scheme and the BLISS signature is believed to be related to, but not provably reducible to, the closest vector problem (CVP) in a lattice.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The Post-Quantum Cryptography Study Group sponsored by the European Commission suggested that the Stehle–Steinfeld variant of NTRU, which *does* have a security reduction, be studied for long term use instead of the original NTRU algorithm.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Unbalanced Oil and Vinegar signature schemes are asymmetric cryptographic primitives based on multivariate polynomials over a finite field ⁠ $\mathbb {F}$ ⁠.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Bulygin, Petzoldt, and Buchmann have shown a reduction of generic multivariate quadratic UOV systems to the NP-Hard multivariate quadratic equation solving problem.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In 2005, Luis Garcia proved that there was a security reduction of Merkle Hash Tree signatures to the security of the underlying hash function.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Garcia showed in his paper that if computationally one-way hash functions exist then the Merkle Hash Tree signature is provably secure.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Therefore, use of a hash function with a provable reduction of security to a known hard problem would have a provable security reduction of the Merkle tree signature to that known hard problem.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The Post-Quantum Cryptography Study Group sponsored by the European Commission has recommended use of the Merkle signature scheme for long term security protection against quantum computers.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The McEliece Encryption System has a security reduction to the syndrome decoding problem (SDP).
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The Post-Quantum Cryptography Study Group sponsored by the European Commission has recommended the use of this cryptography for long term protection against attack by a quantum computer.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In 2016, Wang proposed a random linear code encryption scheme RLCE which is based on McEliece schemes.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] A RLCE scheme can be constructed using any linear code such as Reed-Solomon code by inserting random columns in the underlying linear code generator matrix.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Security is related to the problem of constructing an isogeny between two supersingular curves with the same number of points.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The most recent published investigation of the difficulty of this problem, by Delfs and Galbraith, indicates that this problem is as hard as the inventors of the key exchange suggest that it is.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] There is no security reduction to a known NP-hard problem.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] One common characteristic of many post-quantum cryptography algorithms is that they require larger key sizes than commonly used "pre-quantum" public key algorithms.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] There are often tradeoffs to be made in key size, computational efficiency and ciphertext or signature size.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The table below lists some values for different schemes at a 128-bit post-quantum security level.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] A practical consideration on a choice among post-quantum cryptographic algorithms is the effort required to send public keys over the internet.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] From this point of view, the Ring-LWE, NTRU, and SIDH algorithms provide key sizes conveniently under 1 kB, hash-signature public keys come in under 5 kB, and MDPC-based McEliece takes about 1 kB.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] On the other hand, Goppa-based McEliece requires a nearly 1 MB key.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The fundamental idea of using LWE and Ring LWE for key exchange was proposed and filed at the University of Cincinnati in 2011 by Jintai Ding.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The basic idea comes from the associativity of matrix multiplications, and the errors are used to provide the security.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In 2014, Peikert presented a key transport scheme following the same basic idea of Ding's, where the new idea of sending an additional 1 bit signal for rounding in Ding's construction is also used.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] For somewhat greater than 128 bits of security, Singh presents a set of parameters which have 6956-bit public keys for the Peikert's scheme.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The corresponding private key would be roughly 14,000 bits.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In 2015, an authenticated key exchange with provable forward security following the same basic idea of Ding's was presented at Eurocrypt 2015, which is an extension of the HMQV construction in Crypto2005.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The parameters for different security levels from 80 bits to 350 bits, along with the corresponding key sizes are provided in the paper.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] For 128 bits of security in NTRU, `ntruhps2048509` with n = 509 and q = 2048 was selected in the NIST submission in September 2020.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This results in a public key of 699 bytes and a corresponding private key of 935 bytes.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In order to get 128 bits of security for hash based signatures to sign 1 million messages using the fractal Merkle tree method of Naor Shenhav and Wool the public and private key sizes are roughly 36,000 bits in length.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] For 128 bits of security in a McEliece scheme, The European Commission's Post-Quantum Cryptography Study group recommends using a binary Goppa code of length at least *n* = 6960 and dimension at least *k* = 5413, and capable of correcting *t* = 119 errors.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] With these parameters the public key for the McEliece system will be a systematic generator matrix whose non-identity part takes *k* × (*n* − *k*) = 8373911 bits.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The corresponding private key, which consists of the code support with *n* = 6960 elements from GF(213) and a generator polynomial of with *t* = 119 coefficients from GF(213), will be 92,027 bits in length.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The group is also investigating the use of Quasi-cyclic MDPC codes of length at least *n* = 216 + 6 = 65542 and dimension at least *k* = 215 + 3 = 32771, and capable of correcting *t* = 264 errors.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] With these parameters the public key for the McEliece system will be the first row of a systematic generator matrix whose non-identity part takes *k* = 32771 bits.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The private key, a quasi-cyclic parity-check matrix with *d* = 274 nonzero entries on a column (or twice as much on a row), takes no more than *d* × 16 = 4384 bits when represented as the coordinates of the nonzero entries on the first row.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Barreto et al. recommend using a binary Goppa code of length at least *n* = 3307 and dimension at least *k* = 2515, and capable of correcting *t* = 66 errors.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] With these parameters the public key for the McEliece system will be a systematic generator matrix whose non-identity part takes *k* × (*n* − *k*) = 1991880 bits.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The corresponding private key, which consists of the code support with *n* = 3307 elements from GF(212) and a generator polynomial of *t* = 66 coefficients from GF(212), will be 40,476 bits in length.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] For 128 bits of security in the supersingular isogeny Diffie–Hellman (SIDH) method, De Feo, Jao and Plut recommend using a supersingular curve modulo of a 768-bit prime.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] If one uses elliptic curve point compression, the public key will need to be no more than 8x768 or 6144 bits in length.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This makes the number of bits transmitted roughly equivalent to the non-quantum secure RSA and Diffie–Hellman at the same classical security level.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] As a general rule, for 128 bits of security in a symmetric-key–based system, one can safely use key sizes of 256 bits.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The best quantum attack against arbitrary symmetric-key systems is an application of Grover's algorithm, which requires work proportional to the square root of the size of the key space.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] To transmit an encrypted key to a device that possesses the symmetric key necessary to decrypt that key requires roughly 256 bits as well.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] It is clear that symmetric-key systems offer the smallest key sizes for post-quantum cryptography.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] A public-key system demonstrates a property referred to as perfect forward secrecy when it generates random public keys per session for the purposes of key agreement.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This means that the compromise of one message cannot lead to the compromise of others, and also that there is not a single secret value which can lead to the compromise of multiple messages.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Security experts recommend using cryptographic algorithms that support forward secrecy over those that do not.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The reason for this is that forward secrecy can protect against the compromise of long term private keys associated with public/private key pairs.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This is viewed as a means of preventing mass surveillance by intelligence agencies.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Both the Ring-LWE key exchange and supersingular isogeny Diffie–Hellman (SIDH) key exchange can support forward secrecy in one exchange with the other party.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Both the Ring-LWE and SIDH can also be used without forward secrecy by creating a variant of the classic ElGamal encryption variant of Diffie–Hellman.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The other algorithms in this article, such as NTRU, do not support forward secrecy as is.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Any authenticated public key encryption system can be used to build a key exchange with forward secrecy.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The **Open Quantum Safe** (**OQS**) project was started in late 2016 and has the goal of developing and prototyping quantum-resistant cryptography.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] It aims to integrate current post-quantum schemes in one library: **liboqs**. liboqs is an open source C library for quantum-resistant cryptographic algorithms.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] It initially focuses on key exchange algorithms but by now includes several signature schemes.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] It provides a common application programming interface (API) suitable for post-quantum key exchange algorithms, and will collect together various implementations. liboqs will also include a test harness and benchmarking routines to compare performance of post-quantum implementations.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Furthermore, OQS also provides integration of liboqs into OpenSSL.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] A challenge in post-quantum cryptography is the implementation of potentially quantum safe algorithms into existing systems.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] There are tests done, for example by Microsoft Research implementing PICNIC in a PKI using Hardware security modules.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Test implementations for Google's NewHope algorithm have also been done by HSM vendors.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In August 2023, Google released a FIDO2 security key implementation of an ECC/Dilithium hybrid signature schema which was done in partnership with ETH Zürich.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The Signal Protocol has used Post-Quantum Extended Diffie–Hellman (PQXDH) since 2023.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] On February 21, 2024, Apple announced that they were going to upgrade their iMessage protocol with a new PQC protocol called "PQ3", which will use ongoing keying.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Apple stated that, although capable quantum computers do not yet exist, they wanted to mitigate risks from future quantum computers as well as so-called "Harvest now, decrypt later" attack scenarios.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Apple stated that they believe their PQ3 implementation provides protections that "surpass those in all other widely deployed messaging apps", because it uses ongoing keying.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Apple intended to replace the existing iMessage protocol within all supported conversations with PQ3 by the end of 2024.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Apple also defined a scale to make it easier to compare the security properties of messaging apps, with a scale represented by levels ranging from 0 to 3: 0 for no end-to-end by default, 1 for pre-quantum end-to-end by default, 2 for PQC key establishment only (e.g.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] PQXDH), and 3 for PQC key establishment *and* ongoing rekeying (PQ3).
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The Internet Engineering Task Force has prepared an Internet-Draft using PQC algorithms in Messaging Layer Security (MLS).
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] MLS will be used in RCS text messaging in Google Messages and Messages (Apple).
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Blockchain systems commonly rely on public-key cryptography, particularly elliptic-curve digital signature algorithms (ECDSA), to authenticate transactions and control asset ownership.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] These cryptographic schemes are vulnerable to quantum attacks, as Shor’s algorithm can efficiently solve the discrete logarithm problem on which they are based.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In many blockchain protocols, public keys are not revealed until a transaction is executed; however, once exposed, they may become susceptible to quantum attacks if adversaries possess sufficiently advanced quantum capabilities.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This has led to recommendations that users migrate assets to quantum-resistant address schemes prior to the emergence of large-scale quantum computers.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The integration of post-quantum cryptographic algorithms into blockchain systems presents several technical challenges.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Many post-quantum signature schemes require larger key and signature sizes, which can increase transaction size, storage requirements, and network bandwidth usage.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Additionally, higher computational costs for verification may affect scalability and throughput in distributed networks.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Hybrid cryptographic approaches combining classical and post-quantum signatures have been proposed as transitional solutions.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] These approaches aim to maintain backward compatibility while gradually introducing quantum-resistant security mechanisms.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Ongoing research is focused on optimizing post-quantum schemes for decentralized environments while balancing security, efficiency, and scalability requirements.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] While post-quantum algorithms protect data content from future decryption, they do not prevent the interception and storage of the encrypted ciphertext itself (a threat model known as "Harvest now, decrypt later").
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] To mitigate this risk, some network architectures incorporate physical layer security (PLS) or optical chaos alongside PQC.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] By burying the optical signal within the noise floor (negative OSNR) using spectral phase encoding, these physical countermeasures aim to make the transmission unrecordable.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This creates a "defense-in-depth" strategy: physical obfuscation prevents the harvesting of ciphertext entirely, ensuring that no data exists for future quantum decryption, while PQC algorithms provide necessary protection for data stored at the endpoints.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Google has maintained the use of "hybrid encryption" in its use of post-quantum cryptography: whenever a relatively new post-quantum scheme is used, it is combined with a more proven, non-PQ scheme.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This is to ensure that the data are not compromised even if the relatively new PQ algorithm turns out to be vulnerable to non-quantum attacks before Y2Q.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This type of scheme is used in its 2016 and 2019 tests for post-quantum TLS, and in its 2023 FIDO2 key.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] One of the algorithms used in the 2019 test, SIKE, was broken in 2022, but the non-PQ X25519 layer (already used widely in TLS) still protected the data.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Apple's PQ3 and Signal's PQXDH are also hybrid.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The NSA and GCHQ argue against hybrid encryption, claiming that it adds complexity to implementation and transition.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Bernstein, who supports hybrid encryption, argues that the claims are bogus.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Post-quantum cryptography's need is predicated on traditional, established cryptographic problems being quickly solved by a quantum computer.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] However, quantum computers are still under development, and have yet to demonstrate a large scale test of Shor's algorithm, verifying that a quantum speed-up mechanism is possible, and out-performs a classical computer on such problems.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In 2019, a team using the *IBM Q* quantum computer could factor the numbers 15 and 21, but *not* 35.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Other attempts have been made to simulate quantum computers for larger numbers, but the simulations had no quantum advantage (i.e a speed-up over a classical computer).
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] These cryptograpic systems are used worldwide, and have been extensively tested for vulnerabilities for several decades.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Mathematicians Stephen Wolfram and Christopher Wolfram have created simulated models based on Branchial Graphs to mimic quantum mechanics, and by extension can emulate systems utilized by quantum computers.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Their research lead Stephen to publicly express mild doubts about the proposed *quantum speed-up mechanism*'s existence, related to the systematic collapse/unwinding of the entangle quantum states down to a usable, error-corrected solution.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] That is, *doubts* about the mechanism responsible for the *theoretical quantum advantage* utilized by future quantum computers, at scale, where a large number of fully entangled qubits are capable of running Shor's Algorithm against a modern classical problem (e.g.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] RSA-2048, utilizing *integer factorization*).
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In 2013, Edward Snowden's NSA leaks confirmed that the largest supercomputers of the time could not break *correctly implemented* public key crypto systems.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Also, the NSA had not found a mathematical shortcut, despite being the largest employer of mathematicians in the world.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Security analyst and cryptographer, Bruce Schneier, who had access to the Snowden archive, concluded that the math was never broken.
[src:lattice-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Taken in aggregate, if the above criticisms prove to be true, then the need for *post-quantum cryptography* is put into question, along with the need to switch modern business infrastructure onto *less-proven* cryptographic schemes.
